WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:14.000
Oxford Bookworms, Stage 1. The Monkeys Poor by W.W. Jacobs. Chapter 1

00:14.000 --> 00:21.120
It was cold and dark out in the road, and the rain did not stop for a minute. But in

00:21.120 --> 00:28.400
the little living-room of number twelve Castle Road, it was nice and warm. Old Mr. White

00:28.400 --> 00:36.000
and his son Herbert played chess, and Mrs. White sat and watched them. The old woman was

00:36.000 --> 00:40.720
happy because her husband and her son were good friends, and they liked to be together.

00:42.560 --> 00:50.560
Herbert's a good son, she thought. We waited a long time for him, and I was nearly forty when

00:50.640 --> 01:01.520
he was born, but we are a happy family. And old Mrs. White smiled. It was true. Herbert was young,

01:02.160 --> 01:06.640
and he laughed a lot, but his mother and his father laughed with him.

01:08.800 --> 01:12.640
They had not got much money, but they were a very happy little family.

01:12.880 --> 01:22.480
The two men did not talk because they played carefully. The room was quiet, but the noise of the

01:22.480 --> 01:30.240
rain was worse now, and they could hear it on the windows. Suddenly, old Mr. White looked up.

01:30.320 --> 01:41.760
Listen to the rain, he said. Yes, it's a bad night, Herbert answered. It's not a good night to be out,

01:43.120 --> 01:50.800
but is your friend Tom Morris coming tonight? Yes, that's right. He's coming at about seven

01:50.800 --> 02:00.080
o'clock, the old man said. But perhaps this rain? Mr. White did not finish because just

02:00.080 --> 02:06.960
then the young man heard a noise. Listen, Herbert said. There's someone at the door now.

02:08.560 --> 02:16.480
I didn't hear a noise, his father answered, but he got up from his chair and went to open the front

02:16.480 --> 02:24.160
door. Mrs. White got up too and began to put things away. Mr. White said,

02:25.120 --> 02:34.960
Come in, come in, Tom. It's wonderful to see you again. What a bad night. Give me your coat,

02:35.520 --> 02:39.680
and then come into the living room. It's nice and warm in there.

02:42.160 --> 02:48.480
The front door was open, and in the living room, Mrs. White and Herbert felt the cold.

02:49.280 --> 02:54.800
Then Mr. White came back into the living room with a big red-faced man.

02:56.400 --> 03:04.240
This is Tom Morris. Mr. White told his wife and son. We were friends when we were young.

03:05.120 --> 03:14.960
We worked together before Tom went to India. Tom, this is my wife, and this is our son, Herbert.

03:15.840 --> 03:25.040
Please to meet you, Tom Morris said. Please to meet you, Mr. Morris. Mrs. White answered.

03:25.920 --> 03:32.320
Please come and sit down. Yes, come on, Tom. Mr. White said,

03:33.120 --> 03:41.200
Over here, it's nice and warm. Thank you. The big man answered, and he sat down.

03:42.080 --> 03:50.160
Let's have some whiskey, old Mr. White said. You need something to warm you on a cold night?

03:51.520 --> 03:57.280
He got out a bottle of whiskey, and the two old friends began to drink and talk.

03:58.720 --> 04:06.400
The little family listened with interest to this visitor from far away, and he told them many strange stories.

04:12.080 --> 04:16.240
Chapter 2

04:19.200 --> 04:25.840
After some time, Tom Morris stopped talking, and Mr. White said to his wife and son,

04:27.120 --> 04:34.720
Tom was a soldier in India for 21 years. India is a wonderful country.

04:35.520 --> 04:43.920
Yes, Herbert said. I'd like to go there. Oh, Herbert, his mother cried.

04:45.280 --> 04:48.640
She was afraid because she did not want to lose her son.

04:50.320 --> 04:58.160
I wanted to go to India too, her husband said. But it's better for you here,

04:59.040 --> 05:06.080
the soldier said quickly. But you saw a lot of strange and wonderful things in India.

05:07.120 --> 05:14.320
I want to see them too one day, Mr. White said. The soldier put down his whiskey.

05:15.200 --> 05:18.400
No, he cried. Stay here.

05:19.280 --> 05:27.280
Old Mr. White did not stop. But your stories were interesting, he said, to Tom Morris.

05:28.160 --> 05:32.560
What did you begin to say about a monkey's paw?

05:33.520 --> 05:40.240
Nothing, Morris answered quickly. Well, nothing important.

05:41.040 --> 05:51.200
A monkey's paw, Mrs. White said. Come on, Mr. Morris. Tell us about it, Herbert said.

05:53.200 --> 05:58.400
Morris took his whiskey in his hand, but suddenly he put it down again.

06:00.080 --> 06:05.280
Slowly he put his hand into the pocket of his coat, and the White family watched him.

06:06.240 --> 06:13.520
What is it? What is it? Mrs. White cried. Morris said nothing.

06:15.040 --> 06:20.400
He took his hand out of his pocket. The White family watched carefully.

06:21.760 --> 06:26.560
And in the soldier's hand, they saw something little and dirty.

06:28.000 --> 06:33.360
Mrs. White moved back, afraid. But her son, Herbert, took it,

06:34.160 --> 06:35.600
and looked at it carefully.

06:37.120 --> 06:41.840
Well, what is it? Mr. White asked his friend.

06:43.520 --> 06:50.560
Look at it, the soldier answered. It's a little poor. A monkey's paw.

06:52.080 --> 06:56.720
A monkey's paw, Herbert said, and he laughed.

06:57.680 --> 07:03.680
Why do you carry a monkey's paw in your pocket, Mr. Morris? He asked the old soldier.

07:05.120 --> 07:13.840
Well, you see, Morris said, this monkey's paw is magic. Herbert laughed again.

07:14.880 --> 07:21.920
But the soldier said, don't laugh, boy. Remember, you're young.

07:22.880 --> 07:29.120
I'm old now, and in India I saw many strange things.

07:30.800 --> 07:40.480
He stopped talking for a minute, and then he said, this monkey's paw can do strange and wonderful things.

07:41.600 --> 07:48.080
An old Indian gave the paw to one of my friends. My friend was a soldier, too.

07:48.960 --> 07:55.360
This paw is magic, because it can give three wishes to three people.

07:56.720 --> 07:59.280
Who wonderful, Herbert said.

08:00.240 --> 08:05.280
But these three wishes don't bring happiness, the soldier said.

08:06.480 --> 08:13.680
The old Indian wanted to teach us something. It's never good to want to change things.

08:14.320 --> 08:22.000
Well, did your friend have three wishes? Herbert asked the old soldier.

08:23.440 --> 08:32.080
Yes, Morris answered quietly. And his third and last wish was to die.

08:34.400 --> 08:41.520
Mr. and Mrs. White listened to the story, and they felt afraid. But Herbert asked,

08:41.520 --> 08:43.920
and did he die?

08:45.200 --> 08:54.480
Yes, he did, Morris said. He had no family, so his things came to me when he died.

08:55.680 --> 09:02.160
The monkey's paw was with his things, but he told me about it before he died.

09:03.120 --> 09:05.120
Tom Morris finished quietly.

09:05.600 --> 09:13.120
What were his first two wishes, then? Herbert asked. What did he ask for?

09:14.960 --> 09:20.320
I don't know. He didn't want to tell me, the soldier answered.

09:22.720 --> 09:27.440
For a minute or two, everybody was quiet. But then Herbert said,

09:27.680 --> 09:33.200
and you, Mr. Morris, did you have three wishes?

09:34.560 --> 09:46.640
Yes, I did, Morris answered. I was young. I wanted many things, a fast car, money.

09:49.120 --> 09:52.880
Morris stopped for a minute, and then he said with difficulty,

09:53.040 --> 10:04.400
my wife and my young son died in an accident in the car. Without them, I didn't want the money.

10:05.600 --> 10:14.080
So in the end, I wished to lose it. But it was too late. My wife and my child were dead.

10:14.880 --> 10:22.560
The room was very quiet. The white family looked at the unhappy face of the old soldier.

10:23.520 --> 10:34.000
Then Mr. White said, why do you want the paw now? You don't need it. You can give it to someone.

10:35.200 --> 10:43.280
How can I give it to someone? The soldier said. The monkey's paw brings unhappiness with it,

10:43.760 --> 10:50.960
will give it to me, Mr. White said. Perhaps this time it... No,

10:51.600 --> 10:58.000
Tom Morris cried. You're my friend. I can't give it to you.

10:59.440 --> 11:10.000
Then after a minute, he said, I can't give it to you. But of course, you can take it from me.

11:10.960 --> 11:15.840
But remember, this monkey's paw brings unhappiness.

11:17.840 --> 11:26.320
Old Mr. White did not listen, and he did not think. Quickly, he put out his hand, and he took the paw.

11:28.080 --> 11:32.640
Tom Morris looked unhappy, but Mr. White did not want to wait.

11:33.280 --> 11:46.080
What do I do now? He asked his friend. Yes. Come on, father. Herbert said, make a wish, and he laughed.

11:48.000 --> 11:54.400
The soldier said nothing, and Mr. White asked him again. What do I do now?

11:55.280 --> 12:01.760
At first, the old soldier did not answer. But in the end, he said quietly,

12:02.720 --> 12:15.600
OK. But remember, be careful. Think before you make your wish. Yes, yes, Mr. White said.

12:16.480 --> 12:26.400
Take the paw in your right hand, and then make your wish. But Tom Morris began. Yes, we know,

12:26.400 --> 12:37.760
Herbert said, be careful. Just then, old Mrs. White stood up, and she began to get the dinner.

12:37.760 --> 12:43.760
Her husband looked at her. Then he smiled and said to her,

12:44.400 --> 12:54.960
come on, help me. What can I wish for? We need money, of course. Mrs. White laughed,

12:54.960 --> 13:03.200
but she thought for a minute, and then she said, well, I'm getting old now,

13:03.200 --> 13:12.800
and sometimes it's difficult to do everything. Perhaps I need four hands and not two. Yes,

13:13.200 --> 13:17.360
ask the poor to give me two more hands.

13:18.800 --> 13:24.880
OK then, her husband said, and he took the monkey's paw in his right hand.

13:26.560 --> 13:33.920
Everybody watched him, and for a minute he waited. Then he opened his mouth to make his wish.

13:34.240 --> 13:40.800
Suddenly Tom Morris stood up. Don't do it, he cried.

13:40.800 --> 13:50.160
The old soldier's face was white. Herbert and his mother laughed, but Mr. White looked at Tom's face.

13:50.160 --> 13:59.760
Old Mr. White was afraid, and he put the monkey's paw into his pocket. After a minute or two,

13:59.840 --> 14:03.120
they sat down at the table and began to have dinner.

14:04.480 --> 14:08.960
The soldier told the family many strange and wonderful stories about India.

14:10.000 --> 14:15.360
They forgot the monkey's paw. And because the soldier's stories were interesting,

14:16.080 --> 14:23.840
they asked him many questions about India. When Tom Morris stood up to leave, it was very late.

14:24.720 --> 14:29.920
Thank you for a very nice evening, Morris said to the family.

14:30.800 --> 14:35.440
And thank you for a very good dinner, he said to Mrs. White.

14:37.200 --> 14:40.080
It was a wonderful evening for us, Tom.

14:41.120 --> 14:45.760
Old Mr. White answered. Your stories were very interesting.

14:46.800 --> 14:51.920
Our life isn't very exciting, and we don't have the money to visit India.

14:52.880 --> 14:58.800
So please come again soon. You can tell us some more stories about India.

15:00.800 --> 15:15.760
Then the old soldier put on his coat. He said goodbye to the White family and went out into the rain.

15:16.000 --> 15:18.240
Chapter 3

15:20.800 --> 15:27.680
It was nearly midnight. In their warm living room, the two old people and their sons sat

15:27.680 --> 15:29.760
and talked about the soldier's stories.

15:31.200 --> 15:39.360
India is a wonderful country, Mr. White said. What exciting stories. It was a good evening.

15:40.320 --> 15:47.680
Mrs. White stood up to take some things into the kitchen, but she stopped and listened to Herbert and his father.

15:48.480 --> 15:57.600
Yes, Herbert said. Morris told some interesting stories. But of course, some of them weren't true.

15:58.400 --> 16:06.720
Oh, Herbert, Mrs. White said. Well, mother, that story about the monkey's paw wasn't true.

16:07.680 --> 16:14.800
A dirty little monkey's paw isn't magic, but it was a good story. And Herbert smiled.

16:16.480 --> 16:21.120
Well, I think you're right, Herbert, his mother said.

16:22.640 --> 16:33.680
I don't know, Mr. White said quietly. Perhaps the story was true. Strange things can happen sometimes.

16:34.640 --> 16:37.040
Mrs. White looked at her husband.

16:38.960 --> 16:43.600
Did you give some money to Tom Morris for that paw? She asked.

16:44.720 --> 16:50.160
We don't have money to give away for nothing. Mrs. White was angry now.

16:51.440 --> 17:00.880
Well, yes, her husband answered. I did, but not much. And at first he didn't want to take it.

17:01.440 --> 17:03.280
He wanted the monkey's paw.

17:04.640 --> 17:13.040
Well, he can't have it. Herbert laughed. It's our paw now. And we're going to be rich and happy.

17:14.320 --> 17:16.800
Come on, father. Make a wish.

17:18.800 --> 17:21.440
Old Mr. White took the paw from his pocket.

17:23.040 --> 17:29.360
Okay, Herbert. But what am I going to ask for? I have everything.

17:30.080 --> 17:38.480
You, your mother, what do I need? Money, of course. Herbert answered quickly.

17:39.040 --> 17:46.240
We need money. You're always thinking about money. That's because we haven't got very much of it.

17:47.440 --> 17:58.000
With money, you can pay for this house. It can be your house. Go on, father. Wish for 30,000 pounds.

17:59.760 --> 18:03.920
Herbert stopped talking, and his old father thought for a minute.

18:05.280 --> 18:09.200
The room was quiet, and they could hear the rain on the windows.

18:10.800 --> 18:14.320
Then Mr. White took the monkey's paw in his right hand.

18:15.440 --> 18:19.600
He was afraid, but he looked at his wife and she smiled at him.

18:20.480 --> 18:22.960
Go on, she said.

18:24.640 --> 18:27.600
Slowly and carefully, Mr. White said,

18:29.200 --> 18:33.840
I wish for 30,000 pounds.

18:35.200 --> 18:40.160
Suddenly, he gave a cry, and Mrs. White and Herbert ran to him.

18:41.600 --> 18:44.400
What's the matter, father? Herbert asked.

18:45.200 --> 18:52.080
It moved, Mr. White cried. The monkey's paw! It moved!

18:53.600 --> 18:59.360
They looked at the paw. It was now on the floor and not in the old man's hand.

19:00.640 --> 19:05.440
The family watched it, and they waited. But it did not move again.

19:07.440 --> 19:12.160
So the little family sat down again, and they waited. Nothing happened.

19:13.120 --> 19:20.560
The noise of the rain on the windows was worse now, and their little living room did not feel nice and warm.

19:22.000 --> 19:26.720
Mrs. White said, it's cold. Let's go to bed.

19:28.160 --> 19:31.920
Mr. White did not answer, and in the end, Herbert said,

19:32.960 --> 19:38.720
Well, there's no money, father. Your friend's story wasn't true.

19:39.600 --> 19:44.720
But Mr. White did not answer. He sat quietly and said nothing.

19:46.880 --> 19:49.760
After some time, Mrs. White said to her husband,

19:51.200 --> 19:58.080
Are you okay? Yes. Yes, the old man answered.

19:59.200 --> 20:06.960
But for a minute or two, I was afraid. Well, we needed that money, Mrs. White said,

20:07.760 --> 20:13.280
But we aren't going to get it. I'm tired. I'm going to bed.

20:15.440 --> 20:20.720
After Mrs. White went to bed, the two men sat and smoked for some time.

20:22.160 --> 20:31.040
Then Herbert said, Well, father, I'm going to bed too. Perhaps the money is in a bag under your bed.

20:31.760 --> 20:32.800
Good night, father.

20:34.160 --> 20:36.880
And Herbert laughed and went out of the room.

20:38.960 --> 20:42.640
Old Mr. White sat in the cold living room for a long time.

20:43.920 --> 20:52.000
The candle died, and it was dark. Suddenly, the old man saw a face at the window.

20:53.120 --> 20:59.360
Quickly, he looked again. But there was nothing there. He felt afraid.

21:00.080 --> 21:05.360
Slowly, he stood up and left the cold, dark room.

21:15.680 --> 21:16.400
Chapter 4

21:19.920 --> 21:26.320
The next morning the winter sun came through the window, and the house felt nice and warm again.

21:26.480 --> 21:31.600
Mr. White felt better, and he smiled at his wife and son.

21:32.240 --> 21:37.680
The family sat down to have breakfast, and they began to talk about the day.

21:38.720 --> 21:46.640
The monkey's paw was on a little table near the window, but nobody looked at it, and nobody thought about it.

21:47.520 --> 21:55.120
I'm going to the shops this morning, Mrs. White said. I want to get something nice for dinner.

21:55.920 --> 21:59.760
Are you going to come with me? She asked her husband.

22:00.800 --> 22:08.400
No, I'm going to have a quiet morning. I'm going to read. Her husband answered.

22:08.400 --> 22:09.520
Her husband answered.

22:10.800 --> 22:18.000
Well, I'm not going to go out this evening, Herbert said. So we can go to bed early tonight.

22:18.720 --> 22:20.320
We were very late last night.

22:22.320 --> 22:29.440
And we aren't going to have stories about monkey's paws, Mrs. White said. She was angry.

22:30.960 --> 22:34.720
Why did we listen to your friend? She asked her husband.

22:35.680 --> 22:38.240
A monkey's paw can't give you things.

22:39.680 --> 22:42.880
She stopped, but the two men did not answer her.

22:43.920 --> 22:50.320
Thirty thousand pounds, she said quietly. We needed that money.

22:52.560 --> 22:55.200
Just then Herbert looked at the clock and stood up.

22:56.720 --> 23:02.480
I'm going to work, he said. Perhaps the postman has got the money for you in a letter.

23:03.280 --> 23:09.520
Remember, I want some of it too. Herbert laughed and his mother laughed too.

23:10.480 --> 23:18.960
Don't laugh, son, Mr. White said. Tom Morris is an old friend and he thinks the story is true.

23:19.920 --> 23:26.640
Perhaps it is. Well, leave some of the money for me. Herbert laughed again.

23:27.440 --> 23:30.800
His mother laughed too and she went to the door with him.

23:32.240 --> 23:38.640
Goodbye, mother. Herbert said happily. Get something nice for dinner this evening at the shops.

23:39.520 --> 23:46.000
I'm always hungry after a day at work. I know you are, Mrs. White answered.

23:48.000 --> 23:51.440
Herbert left the house and walked quickly down the road.

23:52.640 --> 23:55.520
His mother stood at the door for some time and watched him.

23:56.960 --> 24:02.560
The winter sun was warm, but suddenly she felt very cold.

24:09.680 --> 24:10.480
Chapter 5

24:13.200 --> 24:16.240
Slowly, old Mrs. White went back into the house.

24:17.520 --> 24:20.720
Her husband looked up and saw something strange in her face.

24:21.680 --> 24:24.320
What's the matter? He asked.

24:25.520 --> 24:30.240
Nothing, his wife answered and she sat down to finish her breakfast.

24:31.840 --> 24:36.720
She began to think about Tom Morris again and suddenly she said to her husband,

24:38.240 --> 24:45.200
your friend drank a lot of whiskey last night. Her monkey's poor. What a story.

24:46.080 --> 24:53.920
Mr. White did not answer her because just then the postman arrived. He brought two letters for them.

24:54.800 --> 24:56.000
But there was no money in them.

24:58.160 --> 25:02.560
After breakfast, the two old people forgot about the money and the monkey's poor.

25:04.240 --> 25:11.040
Later in the day, at about one o'clock, Mr. and Mrs. White sat down to eat and then they

25:11.120 --> 25:16.080
began to talk about money again. They did not have very much money,

25:16.640 --> 25:18.560
so they often needed to talk about it.

25:19.760 --> 25:24.960
That's thirty thousand pounds, Mrs. White said. We need it.

25:26.480 --> 25:33.280
But it didn't come this morning. Her husband answered. Let's forget it. Then he said,

25:34.160 --> 25:41.760
but that thing moved. The monkey's poor moved in my hand. Tom's story was true.

25:43.120 --> 25:50.640
You drank a lot of whiskey last night. Perhaps the poor didn't move. Mrs. White answered.

25:51.200 --> 25:59.040
It moved. Mr. White cried angrily. At first his wife did not answer, but then she said,

26:00.000 --> 26:08.800
well, Herbert laughed about it. Suddenly she stopped talking. She stood up and went over to the window.

26:09.840 --> 26:12.400
What's the matter? Her husband asked.

26:13.680 --> 26:21.680
There's a man in front of our house, Mrs. White answered. He's a stranger, very tall and well dressed.

26:22.480 --> 26:29.440
He's looking at our house. Oh, no. It's OK. He's going away.

26:30.880 --> 26:35.280
Come and sit down. Finish eating, Mr. White said.

26:36.880 --> 26:39.360
The old woman did not listen to her husband.

26:40.960 --> 26:51.040
He isn't going away. She went on. He's coming back. I don't know him. He's a stranger. Yes.

26:51.760 --> 26:59.920
He's very well dressed. Suddenly Mrs. White stopped. She was very excited. He's coming to the door.

27:00.800 --> 27:06.160
Perhaps he's bringing the money. And she ran out of the room to open the front door.

27:07.760 --> 27:14.160
The tall, well dressed stranger stood there. For a minute, he said nothing. But then he began,

27:14.960 --> 27:19.520
good afternoon. I'm looking for Mr. and Mrs. White.

27:20.960 --> 27:26.080
Well, I'm Mrs. White, the old woman answered. What can I do for you?

27:27.280 --> 27:35.760
At first the stranger did not answer. But then he said, Mrs. White, I'm from Moore and Meggins.

27:36.800 --> 27:38.560
Can I come in and talk to you?

27:39.360 --> 27:44.960
Moore and Meggins had a big factory, and Herbert White worked there on the machinery.

27:45.760 --> 27:50.560
Yes, of course, Mrs. White answered. Please come in.

27:51.760 --> 27:57.360
The well dressed stranger came into the little living room, and Mr. White stood up.

27:58.560 --> 28:06.560
Are you Mr. White? The stranger began. Then he went on. I'm from Moore and Meggins.

28:07.440 --> 28:11.760
Mrs. White looked at the stranger, and she thought,

28:11.760 --> 28:17.680
perhaps he has the money. But why Moore and Meggins?

28:17.680 --> 28:22.080
And his face is very unhappy. Why?

28:22.080 --> 28:26.080
Suddenly the old woman was afraid.

28:26.080 --> 28:33.040
Please sit down, Mr. White began. But now his wife could not wait.

28:34.000 --> 28:37.840
What's the matter? She cried. Is Herbert?

28:38.880 --> 28:40.400
She could not finish the question.

28:41.920 --> 28:47.040
The stranger did not look at their faces, and Mr. White began to be afraid too.

28:48.160 --> 28:56.320
Please tell us, he said, I'm very sorry, the man from Moore and Meggins began.

28:58.080 --> 29:00.960
He stopped for a minute, and then he began again.

29:01.360 --> 29:07.760
I'm very sorry, but this morning there was an accident at the factory.

29:07.760 --> 29:14.160
What's the matter? Is Herbert okay? Mrs. White cried again.

29:14.160 --> 29:18.560
Well, the man began slowly.

29:18.560 --> 29:20.560
You see, in hospital?

29:20.560 --> 29:24.560
The old woman asked, very afraid now.

29:24.560 --> 29:30.160
Yes, but the stranger looked at Mrs. White.

29:30.160 --> 29:32.400
Looked at Mrs. White's face and stopped.

29:34.480 --> 29:38.720
Is he dead? Is Herbert dead?

29:39.760 --> 29:41.360
Mr. White asked quietly.

29:42.320 --> 29:44.400
Dead? Mrs. White cried.

29:44.960 --> 29:52.240
Oh, no. Please. Not dead. Not Herbert. Not our son.

29:54.640 --> 29:58.640
Suddenly the old woman stopped because she saw the stranger's face.

30:00.160 --> 30:04.640
Then the two old people knew. Their son was dead.

30:06.080 --> 30:10.960
Old Mrs. White began to cry quietly, and Mr. White put his arm around her.

30:12.720 --> 30:15.680
Some time later the man from Moore and Meggins said,

30:17.280 --> 30:22.720
it was the machinery, an accident. Herbert called help.

30:24.000 --> 30:29.280
The men heard him and ran to him quickly, but they could do nothing.

30:30.320 --> 30:32.480
The next minute he was in the machinery.

30:33.680 --> 30:36.880
I'm very, very sorry. He finished.

30:39.200 --> 30:41.440
For a minute or two the room was quiet.

30:42.880 --> 30:50.640
At last, Mrs. White said, our son, dead, we're never going to see him again.

30:51.760 --> 30:53.760
What are we going to do without him?

30:54.640 --> 31:00.400
Her husband said, he was our son. We loved him.

31:02.240 --> 31:04.160
Then Mrs. White asked the stranger,

31:05.600 --> 31:12.960
can we see him? Can we see our son? Please take me to him. I want to see my son.

31:14.240 --> 31:16.160
But the stranger answered quickly.

31:16.960 --> 31:20.480
No, he said, it's better not to see him.

31:21.280 --> 31:26.800
They couldn't stop the machinery quickly. He was in there for a long time.

31:27.840 --> 31:30.960
And at first they couldn't get him out. He was...

31:31.920 --> 31:36.640
The man stopped. Then he said, don't go to see him.

31:38.480 --> 31:43.840
The stranger went over to the window because he did not want to see the faces of the two old people.

31:44.800 --> 31:48.960
He said nothing, but he stood there for some time and he waited.

31:51.280 --> 31:54.880
Then he went back to the old people and began to talk again.

31:56.960 --> 32:03.840
There's one more thing, he said. Your son worked for more and Megan's for six years

32:03.840 --> 32:10.240
and he was a good worker. Now more and Megan's want to help you at this unhappy time.

32:11.520 --> 32:16.480
Again the stranger stopped. After a minute he began again.

32:17.360 --> 32:24.320
More and Megan's want to give you some money. Then he put something into Mr. White's hand.

32:25.760 --> 32:32.640
Old Mr. White did not look at the money in his hand. Slowly he stood up and looked at the stranger,

32:32.640 --> 32:33.680
afraid.

32:35.200 --> 32:42.080
How much? Mr. White asked very quietly. He did not want to hear the answer.

32:42.960 --> 32:46.960
Thirty thousand pounds, the stranger said.

32:55.840 --> 32:56.640
Chapter 6

32:58.960 --> 33:03.280
Three days later in the big new cemetery two miles from their house,

33:03.840 --> 33:06.960
the two old people said goodbye to their dead son.

33:08.400 --> 33:10.880
Then they went back to their dark old house.

33:12.560 --> 33:18.320
They did not want to live without Herbert, but they waited for something good to happen,

33:18.320 --> 33:26.000
something to help them. The days went by very slowly. Sometimes they did not talk

33:26.000 --> 33:31.120
because there was nothing to say without Herbert, and so the days felt very long.

33:33.440 --> 33:39.680
Then one night, about a week later, Mrs. White got out of bed because she could not sleep.

33:40.560 --> 33:47.200
She sat by the window and she watched and waited for her son. He did not come and she

33:47.200 --> 33:53.520
began to cry quietly. In the dark her husband heard her and he called,

33:54.240 --> 34:02.800
come back to bed. It's cold out there. It's colder for my son. His wife answered,

34:03.600 --> 34:09.760
he's out there in the cold cemetery. Mrs. White did not go back to bed,

34:10.640 --> 34:17.920
but Mr. White was old and tired and the bed was warm. So in the end he went to sleep again.

34:19.360 --> 34:21.520
Suddenly he heard a cry from his wife.

34:22.400 --> 34:29.520
The poor, she cried, the monkey's poor. She came back to the bed and stood there.

34:30.320 --> 34:36.800
What is it? What's the matter? Mr. White cried. He sat up in bed.

34:37.760 --> 34:44.160
What's the matter? He thought. Why is she excited? What's she talking about?

34:45.040 --> 34:49.280
He looked at his wife. Her face was very white in the dark.

34:50.240 --> 34:58.160
I want it, she said quietly. And you've got it. Give it to me. Please.

34:59.200 --> 35:05.840
What? Mr. White asked. The monkey's poor, Mrs. White said. Where is it?

35:06.960 --> 35:15.040
It's downstairs, Mr. White answered. Why? Mrs. White began to laugh and cry.

35:15.840 --> 35:22.480
We could have two more wishes, she cried. We had one, but there are two more.

35:23.680 --> 35:31.360
Oh, no. Not again. Think, woman. Mr. White cried. But Mrs. White did not listen.

35:32.720 --> 35:39.840
Quickly, she said, go and get the poor. We're going to wish for our boy to come back to us.

35:40.800 --> 35:47.200
No. Mr. White cried. You're mad. Get it. Get it quickly.

35:47.920 --> 35:57.520
Mrs. White cried again. Mr. White said again, think, woman. Think. Our boy was in the machinery

35:57.520 --> 36:05.680
for a long time. They didn't want to show him to us. Think. Do you want to see his body?

36:06.640 --> 36:12.000
Yes. He's my son. I'm not afraid of him. She answered.

36:13.120 --> 36:21.040
You don't understand, Mr. White said sadly, but he went downstairs to look for the monkey's poor.

36:23.200 --> 36:27.200
In the living room, it was dark, and Mr. White did not have a candle.

36:28.560 --> 36:33.280
Slowly, he went across the room, and he put out his hand for the monkey's poor.

36:34.240 --> 36:37.360
He touched it, and quickly took his hand away again.

36:38.640 --> 36:44.320
No, he thought. I can't. I don't want to see Herbert.

36:45.120 --> 36:49.040
His face, after he was in the machinery, no.

36:50.960 --> 36:55.680
Then he thought about his wife, and he put out his hand and took the poor.

36:56.080 --> 37:02.640
In the bedroom, his wife waited. She saw the paw in Mr. White's hand and cried,

37:02.640 --> 37:13.760
quick, make the wish. I can't. Mr. White answered. Remember, he died in the machinery.

37:13.760 --> 37:21.360
Make the wish. I'm not afraid of my own son. Mrs. White cried again.

37:21.440 --> 37:28.720
Mr. White looked sadly at his wife, but he took the paw in his right hand and said slowly,

37:28.720 --> 37:38.720
I wish for my son, Herbert, to come back to us. Then he sat down in the nearest chair.

37:38.720 --> 37:43.760
But Mrs. White went over to the window and looked out into the road.

37:43.760 --> 37:48.480
She stayed there for a long time, and she did not move.

37:48.560 --> 37:53.760
Nothing happened. The monkey's paw could not do it.

37:53.760 --> 38:03.200
Thank God, Mr. White said, and he went back to bed. Soon Mrs. White went to bed, too.

38:03.200 --> 38:13.120
Chapter 7

38:15.360 --> 38:19.280
But they did not sleep. They waited, and they listened.

38:20.960 --> 38:25.680
In the end Mr. White got up to get a candle because the dark made him more afraid.

38:26.640 --> 38:32.960
He began to go downstairs, but suddenly he heard a noise at the front door.

38:34.480 --> 38:37.920
He stopped, and he listened. He could not move.

38:39.360 --> 38:46.400
Then the noise came again. This time he ran. He ran upstairs, back into the bedroom,

38:46.400 --> 38:51.360
and he closed the door behind him. But again the noise came.

38:52.160 --> 38:57.120
What's that? Mrs. White cried, and she sat up in bed.

38:57.120 --> 39:02.720
Nothing. Go to sleep again. Her husband answered.

39:03.920 --> 39:07.360
But Mrs. White listened, and the noise came again.

39:08.560 --> 39:14.640
It's Herbert. It's Herbert, she cried. I'm going to open the door for him.

39:15.680 --> 39:18.960
And she got out of bed and ran to the door of the bedroom.

39:19.760 --> 39:22.720
Mr. White got there first and stopped her.

39:22.720 --> 39:29.200
No! He cried. Think! But it's my boy. It's Herbert!

39:29.200 --> 39:35.680
She answered. No! Don't go! Don't! Her husband cried again.

39:36.880 --> 39:42.400
But Mrs. White did not listen to him. She opened the bedroom door and ran from the room.

39:43.200 --> 39:46.960
I'm coming, Herbert. I'm coming! She called.

39:48.160 --> 39:55.840
Mr. White ran after her. Stop! He cried. Remember! Herbert died in the machinery.

39:56.480 --> 39:58.240
You don't want to see him.

39:59.840 --> 40:03.360
For a minute Mrs. White stopped and looked at her husband.

40:04.400 --> 40:08.560
But then the noise came again, and she began to run downstairs.

40:09.360 --> 40:11.680
Help me! Help me!

40:12.560 --> 40:16.720
She called to her husband. But Mr. White did not move.

40:17.840 --> 40:21.680
The paw, he thought. Where's the monkey's paw?

40:23.360 --> 40:28.160
He ran back into the bedroom. Quick, he thought. Where is it?

40:29.360 --> 40:34.880
At first he could not find it in the dark. Ah! There it was. He had it.

40:35.840 --> 40:39.360
Just that minute he heard his wife downstairs.

40:40.080 --> 40:44.320
Wait! Wait, Herbert! I'm coming! She cried.

40:45.040 --> 40:47.120
She began to open the front door.

40:48.560 --> 40:53.680
At the same time Mr. White took the monkey's paw in his right hand,

40:54.320 --> 40:56.000
and he made his third wish.

40:57.520 --> 41:03.200
Mrs. White gave a long unhappy cry, and her husband ran down to her.

41:04.160 --> 41:12.000
She stood by the open door. Very afraid. Old Mr. White looked out into the dark.

41:13.840 --> 41:19.920
The road was dark and quiet, and there was nobody there.

